is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iritis","Conjunctivitis","Acute angle-close glaucoma","Keratitis","Blepharitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patients use of contact lenses and acute onset pain and decrease in visual acuity, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratitis\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIritis (otherwise known as anterior uveitis) usually presents similarly; rapid onset pain in the eye with decreased visual acuity; however, usually has a predisposing cause such as injury, inflammatory conditions such as sarcoidosis, or medications. Given the use of contact lenses in this patient, they are more likely to have keratitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConjunctivitis often presents with discharge from the eye, redness, and itching, and is unlikely to cause pain or changes in visual acuity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute angle closure glaucoma is an ophthalmic emergency, associated with sudden-onset severe eye pain with nausea, vomiting, blurry vision or halos around lights.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlepharitis usually affects both eyes along the eyelids in a more chronic manner, often associated with other skin changes or inflammatory skin conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Severe eye pain and photophobia in someone who wears contact lens is probably due to keratitis."],"references":["Pflipsen M, Massaquoi M, Wolf S. Evaluation of the Painful Eye. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Jun 15;93(12):991-8. PMID: 27304768."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15027"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"492"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/15027"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-10-02T20:33:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-10-02T20:33:36+10:30"},"relationshi